sql:
SELECT MAX(avg_value) AS max_average_value
FROM (
  SELECT AVG(measurement_value) AS avg_value
  FROM measurements
  GROUP BY measurement_type_id
) AS avg_values;

external_knowledge:
- "researcher_id" and "subject_id" are unique identifiers for researchers and subjects, respectively;
- "avg_measurement_value" represents the average value of measurements taken by a researcher for a specific subject;
- "rank" is a ranking based on the average measurement values, with 1 being the highest;
- "researcher_name" and "subject_notes" provide additional details about the researcher and subject.

- "top researcher" refers to the researcher with the highest number of subjects accessed;
- "garden of knowledge" is a metaphorical expression for the research environment;
- "tended to" means the researcher has taken measurements or accessed data for the subjects.

- "crossed the threshold of three decades" refers to age > 30;
- "the first type of measurement" refers to measurement_type_id = 0;
- "general norm" refers to the overall average measurement value for measurement type 0.

- "Average height and weight" refers to the mean values of height and weight across all subjects;
- "Most frequently used" refers to the measurement type and unit with the highest count of measurements;
- "Most active" refers to the role of the researcher who has taken the most measurements.

sql:
SELECT MAX(measurement_count) AS max_total_measurements
FROM (
    SELECT measurement_type_id, COUNT(measurement_id) AS measurement_count
    FROM measurements
    GROUP BY measurement_type_id
);

external_knowledge:
- 'Minor' refers to individuals under 18 years old;
- 'Adult' refers to individuals between 18 and 64 years old;
- 'Senior' refers to individuals 65 years old and above.

- 'Prime years' refers to the age range between 18 and 59 years old;
- BMI (Body Mass Index) is calculated as weight (in kg) divided by height (in meters) squared;
- BMI categories: 'Underweight' (BMI < 18.5), 'Normal weight' (18.5 ≤ BMI < 25), 'Overweight' (25 ≤ BMI < 30), 'Obese' (BMI ≥ 30).

- "Subjects" refer to the entities or individuals being measured;
- "Measurements" are the recorded data points;
- "Measurement types" are the different kinds of data being collected;
- "Average value" is the mean of the measurement values for each type;
- "Gardener" refers to the researcher who took the first measurement.
